Package org.sbml.squeezer.kinetics

This package contains one class for each supported kinetic law.

See:
          Description

Interface Summary
InterfaceArbitraryEnzymeKinetics Kinetic law objects that implement this interface are able to describe any enzyme-catalyzed process whether or not an enzyme is explicitely assigned to the reaction.
InterfaceBiBiKinetics Kinetic law objects that implement this interface are able to describe enzyme-catalyzed reactions with exactly two reactants (or one reactant with a stoichiometry of two) and two products (or one product with a stoichiometry of two).
InterfaceBiUniKinetics A kinetic law object that implements this interface is able to describe enzyme-catalyzed reactions with two reactants or one reactant with a stoichiometry of two and exactly one product with stoichiometry of one.
InterfaceGeneRegulatoryKinetics A kinetic law object that implements this interface is able to describe gene regulatory processes, i.e., transcription and translation.
InterfaceIntegerStoichiometry All implementing classes represent kinetic equations that require all participating species to take part with integer stoichiometry (reactants and products).
InterfaceIrreversibleKinetics All implementing kinetic laws can be applied to irreversible reactions.
InterfaceModulatedKinetics All implementing kinetic laws allow activatiors or inhibitors to take part in the reaction process.
InterfaceNonEnzymeKinetics If a kinetic law object implements this interface, it can be applied to reactions that are catalyzed by species that are not an enzyme.
InterfaceReversibleKinetics All implementing kinietic laws can bei applied to reversible reactions.
InterfaceUniUniKinetics A kinetic law that implements this interface can be applied to enzyme-catalyzed reactions with exactly one reactant with stoichiometry one and exactly one product with stoichiometry one.
InterfaceZeroProducts Kinetics that allow for an empty list of products.
InterfaceZeroReactants Kinetics that allow for an empty list of reactants.
 

Class Summary
AdditiveModelLinear This class creates an equation based on a linear additive model.
AdditiveModelNonLinear This class creates an equation based on a non-linear additive model.
BasicKineticLaw An abstract super class of specialized kinetic laws, which provides methods for creating Parameter and UnitDefinition objects and maintains all these in dedicated lists.
CommonSaturable This class creates the common saturable rate law according to Liebermeister et al.
ConvenienceKinetics This is the thermodynamically independent form of the convenience kinetics.
DirectSaturable This class creates the direct saturable rate law according to Liebermeister et al.
ForceDependent Force dependent rate law (FD) according to Liebermeister et al 2009.
GeneralizedMassAction This class creates rate equations according to the generalized mass action rate law.
HillEquation This class creates a Hill equation as defined in the paper “Hill Kinetics meets P Systems: A Case Study on Gene Regulatory Networks as Computing Agents in silico and in vivo” of Hinze, T.; Hayat, S.; Lenser, T.; Matsumaru, N., and Dittrich, P., 2007.
HSystem This class creates a non-linear additive equation form Hadeler, K.: “Gedanken zur Parameteridentifikation.” Personal Communication, 2003, and Spieth, C.; Hassis, N.; Streichert, F.; Supper, J.; Beyreuther, K., and Zell, A.
IrrevCompetNonCooperativeEnzymes Irreversible non-exclusive non-cooperative competitive inihibition, a special case of the KineticLaws defined by SBO term identifier 199, 29, 267, or 273 depending on the structure of the reaction.
IrrevNonModulatedNonInteractingEnzymes This class implements SBO:0000150 and all of its special cases.
MichaelisMenten This is the well-known (Henry-) Michaelis-Menten equation and can be found in the SBO under one of the following terms (depending on the specific structure of the underlying Reaction): 28, 199, 265, 269, 275, 276, or 326.
MultiplicativeSaturable This class creates the mulitiplicative saturable kinetic equation according to Liebermeister et al.
NetGeneratorLinear This class creates an equation based on an linear additive model as defined in the paper “The NetGenerator Algorithm: Reconstruction of Gene Regulatory Networks” of Töpfer, S.; Guthke, R.; Driesch, D.; Wötzel, D., and Pfaff 2007
NetGeneratorNonLinear This class creates an equation based on an non-linear additive model as defined in the paper “The NetGenerator Algorithm: Reconstruction of Gene Regulatory Networks” of Töpfer, S.; Guthke, R.; Driesch, D.; Wötzel, D., and Pfaff 2007
OrderedMechanism Rate law for the bi-uni or bi-bi ordered mechanism.
PingPongMechanism Kinetic law that describes the ping-pong reaction mechanism.
RandomOrderMechanism This class creates a kinetic equation according to the random order mechanism (see Cornish-Bowden: Fundamentals of Enzyme Kinetics, p.
ReversiblePowerLaw Represents the reversible power law (RP) from Liebermeister et al.
SpecialHillEquation This class creates Hill equation as defined in the PhD thesis “Modeling Non-Linear Dynamic Phenomena in Biochemical Networks” of Nicole Radde and the paper “Modeling Non-Linear Dynamic Phenomena in Biochemical Networks“ of Nicole Radde and Lars Kaderali.
SSystem This class creates a S-System equation as defined in the papers: Tournier, L.: “Approximation of dynamical systems using S-systems theory: application to biological systems” Spieth, C.; Streichert, F.; Speer, N., and Zell, A.: “Optimizing Topology and Parameters of Gene Regulatory Network Models from Time-Series Experiments” Spieth, C.; Hassis, N.; Streichert, F.; Supper, J.; Beyreuther, K., and Zell, A.: “Comparing Mathematical Models on the Problem of Network Inference” and Hecker, M.; Lambeck, S.; Töpfer, S.; Someren, E.
Vohradsky This class creates an equation based on an additive model as defined in the papers “Neural network model of gene expression.” of Vohradský, J.
Weaver This class creates an equation based on an additive model as defined in the paper “Modeling regulatory networks with weight matrices” of Weaver, D.; Workman, C., and Stormo, G.
ZerothOrderForwardGMAK This class creates generalized mass action rate equations with zeroth order in all reactants.
ZerothOrderReverseGMAK Mass action rate law for zeroth order reverse reactions.
 

Package org.sbml.squeezer.kinetics Description

This package contains one class for each supported kinetic law. There are also specialized exceptions for cases, in which a kinetic law cannot be applied to a certain reaction. This package also contains the KineticLawGenerator, which assigns kinetic laws to reactions within a model.
